#, no-wrap
msgid "Reading an object's SHA-1 content"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../Documentation/technical/hash-function-transition.txt:344
msgid ""
"The SHA-1 content of an object can be read by converting all SHA-256 names "
"of its SHA-256 content references to SHA-1 names using the translation "
"table."
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ~
#: ../Documentation/technical/hash-function-transition.txt:346
#, no-wrap
msgid "Fetch"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../Documentation/technical/hash-function-transition.txt:349
msgid ""
"Fetching from a SHA-1 based server requires translating between SHA-1 and "
"SHA-256 based representations on the fly."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../Documentation/technical/hash-function-transition.txt:353
msgid ""
"SHA-1s named in the ref advertisement that are present on the client can be "
"translated to SHA-256 and looked up as local objects using the translation "
"table."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../Documentation/technical/hash-function-transition.txt:358
msgid ""
"Negotiation proceeds as today. Any \"have\"s generated locally are converted "
"to SHA-1 before being sent to the server, and SHA-1s mentioned by the server "
"are converted to SHA-256 when looking them up locally."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../Documentation/technical/hash-function-transition.txt:362
msgid ""
"After negotiation, the server sends a packfile containing the requested "
"objects. We convert the packfile to SHA-256 format using the following "
"steps:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../Documentation/technical/hash-function-transition.txt:368
msgid ""
"index-pack: inflate each object in the packfile and compute its "
"SHA-1. Objects can contain deltas in OBJ_REF_DELTA format against objects "
"the client has locally. These objects can be looked up using the translation "
"table and their SHA-1 content read as described above to resolve the deltas."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../Documentation/technical/hash-function-transition.txt:375
msgid ""
"topological sort: starting at the \"want\"s from the negotiation phase, walk "
"through objects in the pack and emit a list of them, excluding blobs, in "
"reverse topologically sorted order, with each object coming later in the "
"list than all objects it references.  (This list only contains objects "
"reachable from the \"wants\". If the pack from the server contained "
"additional extraneous objects, then they will be discarded.)"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../Documentation/technical/hash-function-transition.txt:379
msgid ""
"convert to SHA-256: open a new SHA-256 packfile. Read the topologically "
"sorted list just generated. For each object, inflate its SHA-1 content, "
"convert to SHA-256 content, and write it to the SHA-256 pack. Record the new "
"SHA-1<-->SHA-256 mapping entry for use in the idx."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../Documentation/technical/hash-function-transition.txt:382
msgid ""
"sort: reorder entries in the new pack to match the order of objects in the "
"pack the server generated and include blobs. Write a SHA-256 idx file"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../Documentation/technical/hash-function-transition.txt:385
msgid ""
"clean up: remove the SHA-1 based pack file, index, and topologically sorted "
"list obtained from the server in steps 1 and 2."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../Documentation/technical/hash-function-transition.txt:388
msgid ""
"Step 3 requires every object referenced by the new object to be in the "
"translation table. This is why the topological sort step is necessary."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../Documentation/technical/hash-function-transition.txt:394
msgid ""
"As an optimization, step 1 could write a file describing what non-blob "
"objects each object it has inflated from the packfile references. This makes "
"the topological sort in step 2 possible without inflating the objects in the "
"packfile for a second time. The objects need to be inflated again in step 3, "
"for a total of two inflations."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../Documentation/technical/hash-function-transition.txt:398
msgid ""
"Step 4 is probably necessary for good read-time performance. \"git "
"pack-objects\" on the server optimizes the pack file for good data locality "
"(see Documentation/technical/pack-heuristics.txt)."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../Documentation/technical/hash-function-transition.txt:401
msgid ""
"Details of this process are likely to change. It will take some "
"experimenting to get this to perform well."
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ~
#: ../Documentation/technical/hash-function-transition.txt:403
#, no-wrap
msgid "Push"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../Documentation/technical/hash-function-transition.txt:409
msgid ""
"Push is simpler than fetch because the objects referenced by the pushed "
"objects are already in the translation table. The SHA-1 content of each "
"object being pushed can be read as described in the \"Reading an object's "
"SHA-1 content\" section to generate the pack written by git send-pack."
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ~
#: ../Documentation/technical/hash-function-transition.txt:411
#, no-wrap
msgid "Signed Commits"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../Documentation/technical/hash-function-transition.txt:416
msgid ""
"We add a new field \"gpgsig-sha256\" to the commit object format to allow "
"signing commits without relying on SHA-1. It is similar to the existing "
"\"gpgsig\" field. Its signed payload is the SHA-256 content of the commit "
"object with any \"gpgsig\" and \"gpgsig-sha256\" fields removed."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../Documentation/technical/hash-function-transition.txt:418
msgid "This means commits can be signed"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../Documentation/technical/hash-function-transition.txt:420
msgid "using SHA-1 only, as in existing signed commit objects"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../Documentation/technical/hash-function-transition.txt:422
msgid "using both SHA-1 and SHA-256, by using both gpgsig-sha256 and gpgsig fields."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../Documentation/technical/hash-function-transition.txt:423 ../Documentation/technical/hash-function-transition.txt:441
msgid "using only SHA-256, by only using the gpgsig-sha256 field."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../Documentation/technical/hash-function-transition.txt:427
msgid ""
"Old versions of \"git verify-commit\" can verify the gpgsig signature in "
"cases (1) and (2) without modifications and view case (3) as an ordinary "
"unsigned commit."
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ~
#: ../Documentation/technical/hash-function-transition.txt:429
#, no-wrap
msgid "Signed Tags"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../Documentation/technical/hash-function-transition.txt:434
msgid ""
"We add a new field \"gpgsig-sha256\" to the tag object format to allow "
"signing tags without relying on SHA-1. Its signed payload is the SHA-256 "
"content of the tag with its gpgsig-sha256 field and \"-----BEGIN PGP "
"SIGNATURE-----\" delimited in-body signature removed."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../Documentation/technical/hash-function-transition.txt:436
msgid "This means tags can be signed"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../Documentation/technical/hash-function-transition.txt:438
msgid "using SHA-1 only, as in existing signed tag objects"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../Documentation/technical/hash-function-transition.txt:440
msgid ""
"using both SHA-1 and SHA-256, by using gpgsig-sha256 and an in-body "
"signature."
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ~
#: ../Documentation/technical/hash-function-transition.txt:443
#, no-wrap
msgid "Mergetag embedding"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../Documentation/technical/hash-function-transition.txt:446
msgid ""
"The mergetag field in the SHA-1 content of a commit contains the SHA-1 "
"content of a tag that was merged by that commit."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../Documentation/technical/hash-function-transition.txt:449
msgid ""
"The mergetag field in the SHA-256 content of the same commit contains the "
"SHA-256 content of the same tag."
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ~
#: ../Documentation/technical/hash-function-transition.txt:451
#, no-wrap
msgid "Submodules"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../Documentation/technical/hash-function-transition.txt:455
msgid ""
"To convert recorded submodule pointers, you need to have the converted "
"submodule repository in place. The translation table of the submodule can be "
"used to look up the new hash."
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ~
#: ../Documentation/technical/hash-function-transition.txt:457
#, no-wrap
msgid "Loose objects and unreachable objects"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../Documentation/technical/hash-function-transition.txt:460
msgid ""
"Fast lookups in the loose-object-idx require that the number of loose "
"objects not grow too high."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../Documentation/technical/hash-function-transition.txt:464
msgid ""
"\"git gc --auto\" currently waits for there to be 6700 loose objects present "
"before consolidating them into a packfile. We will need to measure to find a "
"more appropriate threshold for it to use."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../Documentation/technical/hash-function-transition.txt:471
msgid ""
"\"git gc --auto\" currently waits for there to be 50 packs present before "
"combining packfiles. Packing loose objects more aggressively may cause the "
"number of pack files to grow too quickly. This can be mitigated by using a "
"strategy similar to Martin Fick's exponential rolling garbage collection "
"script: https://gerrit-review.googlesource.com/c/gerrit/+/35215"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../Documentation/technical/hash-function-transition.txt:479
msgid ""
"\"git gc\" currently expels any unreachable objects it encounters in pack "
"files to loose objects in an attempt to prevent a race when pruning them (in "
"case another process is simultaneously writing a new object that refers to "
"the about-to-be-deleted object). This leads to an explosion in the number of "
"loose objects present and disk space usage due to the objects in delta form "
"being replaced with independent loose objects.  Worse, the race is still "
"present for loose objects."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../Documentation/technical/hash-function-transition.txt:488
msgid ""
"Instead, \"git gc\" will need to move unreachable objects to a new packfile "
"marked as UNREACHABLE_GARBAGE (using the PSRC field; see below). To avoid "
"the race when writing new objects referring to an about-to-be-deleted "
"object, code paths that write new objects will need to copy any objects from "
"UNREACHABLE_GARBAGE packs that they refer to new, non-UNREACHABLE_GARBAGE "
"packs (or loose objects).  UNREACHABLE_GARBAGE are then safe to delete if "
"their creation time (as indicated by the file's mtime) is long enough ago."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../Documentation/technical/hash-function-transition.txt:500
msgid ""
"To avoid a proliferation of UNREACHABLE_GARBAGE packs, they can be combined "
"under certain circumstances. If \"gc.garbageTtl\" is set to greater than one "
"day, then packs created within a single calendar day, UTC, can be coalesced "
"together. The resulting packfile would have an mtime before midnight on that "
"day, so this makes the effective maximum ttl the garbageTtl + 1 day. If "
"\"gc.garbageTtl\" is less than one day, then we divide the calendar day into "
"intervals one-third of that ttl in duration. Packs created within the same "
"interval can be coalesced together. The resulting packfile would have an "
"mtime before the end of the interval, so this makes the effective maximum "
"ttl equal to the garbageTtl * 4/3."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../Documentation/technical/hash-function-transition.txt:503
msgid ""
"This rule comes from Thirumala Reddy Mutchukota's JGit change "
"https://git.eclipse.org/r/90465."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../Documentation/technical/hash-function-transition.txt:506
msgid ""
"The UNREACHABLE_GARBAGE setting goes in the PSRC field of the pack "
"index. More generally, that field indicates where a pack came from:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../Documentation/technical/hash-function-transition.txt:508
msgid "1 (PACK_SOURCE_RECEIVE) for a pack received over the network"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../Documentation/technical/hash-function-transition.txt:510
msgid ""
"2 (PACK_SOURCE_AUTO) for a pack created by a lightweight \"gc --auto\" "
"operation"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../Documentation/technical/hash-function-transition.txt:511
msgid "3 (PACK_SOURCE_GC) for a pack created by a full gc"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../Documentation/technical/hash-function-transition.txt:513
msgid "4 (PACK_SOURCE_UNREACHABLE_GARBAGE) for potential garbage discovered by gc"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../Documentation/technical/hash-function-transition.txt:515
msgid ""
"5 (PACK_SOURCE_INSERT) for locally created objects that were written "
"directly to a pack file, e.g. from \"git add .\""
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../Documentation/technical/hash-function-transition.txt:518
msgid ""
"This information can be useful for debugging and for \"gc --auto\" to make "
"appropriate choices about which packs to coalesce."
msgstr ""

#. type: Title -
#: ../Documentation/technical/hash-function-transition.txt:520
#, no-wrap
msgid "Caveats"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ~
#: ../Documentation/technical/hash-function-transition.txt:522
#, no-wrap
msgid "Invalid objects"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../Documentation/technical/hash-function-transition.txt:528
msgid ""
"The conversion from SHA-1 content to SHA-256 content retains any brokenness "
"in the original object (e.g., tree entry modes encoded with leading 0, tree "
"objects whose paths are not sorted correctly, and commit objects without an "
"author or committer). This is a deliberate feature of the design to allow "
"the conversion to round-trip."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../Documentation/technical/hash-function-transition.txt:532
msgid ""
"More profoundly broken objects (e.g., a commit with a truncated \"tree\" "
"header line) cannot be converted but were not usable by current Git anyway."
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ~
#: ../Documentation/technical/hash-function-transition.txt:534
#, no-wrap
msgid "Shallow clone and submodules"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../Documentation/technical/hash-function-transition.txt:539
msgid ""
"Because it requires all referenced objects to be available in the locally "
"generated translation table, this design does not support shallow clone or "
"unfetched submodules. Protocol improvements might allow lifting this "
"restriction."
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ~
#: ../Documentation/technical/hash-function-transition.txt:541
#, no-wrap
msgid "Alternates"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../Documentation/technical/hash-function-transition.txt:545
msgid ""
"For the same reason, a SHA-256 repository cannot borrow objects from a SHA-1 "
"repository using objects/info/alternates or "
"$GIT_ALTERNATE_OBJECT_REPOSITORIES."
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ~
#: ../Documentation/technical/hash-function-transition.txt:547
#, no-wrap
msgid "git notes"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../Documentation/technical/hash-function-transition.txt:553
msgid ""
"The \"git notes\" tool annotates objects using their SHA-1 name as key.  "
"This design does not describe a way to migrate notes trees to use SHA-256 "
"names. That migration is expected to happen separately (for example using a "
"file at the root of the notes tree to describe which hash it uses)."
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ~
#: ../Documentation/technical/hash-function-transition.txt:555
#, no-wrap
msgid "Server-side cost"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../Documentation/technical/hash-function-transition.txt:561
msgid ""
"Until Git protocol gains SHA-256 support, using SHA-256 based storage on "
"public-facing Git servers is strongly discouraged. Once Git protocol gains "
"SHA-256 support, SHA-256 based servers are likely not to support SHA-1 "
"compatibility, to avoid what may be a very expensive hash re-encode during "
"clone and to encourage peers to modernize."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../Documentation/technical/hash-function-transition.txt:567
msgid ""
"The design described here allows fetches by SHA-1 clients of a personal "
"SHA-256 repository because it's not much more difficult than allowing pushes "
"from that repository. This support needs to be guarded by a configuration "
"option --- servers like git.kernel.org that serve a large number of clients "
"would not be expected to bear that cost."
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ~
#: ../Documentation/technical/hash-function-transition.txt:569
#, no-wrap
msgid "Meaning of signatures"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../Documentation/technical/hash-function-transition.txt:576
msgid ""
"The signed payload for signed commits and tags does not explicitly name the "
"hash used to identify objects. If some day Git adopts a new hash function "
"with the same length as the current SHA-1 (40 hexadecimal digit) or SHA-256 "
"(64 hexadecimal digit) objects then the intent behind the PGP signed payload "
"in an object signature is unclear:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../Documentation/technical/hash-function-transition.txt:581
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"\tobject e7e07d5a4fcc2a203d9873968ad3e6bd4d7419d7\n"
"\ttype commit\n"
"\ttag v2.12.0\n"
"\ttagger Junio C Hamano <gitster@pobox.com> 1487962205 -0800\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../Documentation/technical/hash-function-transition.txt:583
#, no-wrap
msgid "\tGit 2.12\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../Documentation/technical/hash-function-transition.txt:587
msgid ""
"Does this mean Git v2.12.0 is the commit with SHA-1 name "
"e7e07d5a4fcc2a203d9873968ad3e6bd4d7419d7 or the commit with "
"new-40-digit-hash-name e7e07d5a4fcc2a203d9873968ad3e6bd4d7419d7?"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../Documentation/technical/hash-function-transition.txt:592
msgid ""
"Fortunately SHA-256 and SHA-1 have different lengths. If Git starts using "
"another hash with the same length to name objects, then it will need to "
"change the format of signed payloads using that hash to address this issue."
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ~
#: ../Documentation/technical/hash-function-transition.txt:594
#, no-wrap
msgid "Object names on the command line"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../Documentation/technical/hash-function-transition.txt:597
msgid ""
"To support the transition (see Transition plan below), this design supports "
"four different modes of operation:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../Documentation/technical/hash-function-transition.txt:604
msgid ""
"(\"dark launch\") Treat object names input by the user as SHA-1 and convert "
"any object names written to output to SHA-1, but store objects using "
"SHA-256.  This allows users to test the code with no visible behavior change "
"except for performance.  This allows running even tests that assume the "
"SHA-1 hash function, to sanity-check the behavior of the new mode."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../Documentation/technical/hash-function-transition.txt:609
msgid ""
"(\"early transition\") Allow both SHA-1 and SHA-256 object names in "
"input. Any object names written to output use SHA-1. This allows users to "
"continue to make use of SHA-1 to communicate with peers (e.g. by email) that "
"have not migrated yet and prepares for mode 3."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../Documentation/technical/hash-function-transition.txt:615
msgid ""
"(\"late transition\") Allow both SHA-1 and SHA-256 object names in "
"input. Any object names written to output use SHA-256. In this mode, users "
"are using a more secure object naming method by default.  The disruption is "
"minimal as long as most of their peers are in mode 2 or mode 3."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../Documentation/technical/hash-function-transition.txt:620
msgid ""
"(\"post-transition\") Treat object names input by the user as SHA-256 and "
"write output using SHA-256. This is safer than mode 3 because there is less "
"risk that input is incorrectly interpreted using the wrong hash function."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../Documentation/technical/hash-function-transition.txt:622
msgid "The mode is specified in configuration."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../Documentation/technical/hash-function-transition.txt:626
msgid ""
"The user can also explicitly specify which format to use for a particular "
"revision specifier and for output, overriding the mode. For example:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../Documentation/technical/hash-function-transition.txt:628
#, no-wrap
msgid "    git --output-format=sha1 log abac87a^{sha1}..f787cac^{sha256}\n"
msgstr ""

